# What is HTTPS?

**HTTPS (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure)** is the secure version of HTTP.

It encrypts data exchanged between the client and server using **SSL/TLS**.

```text
HTTP
   |
No Encryption
   |
Anyone can read the data
```

```text
HTTPS
   |
Encrypted Data
   |
Safe Communication
```


---
# Why HTTPS?

Without HTTPS

```text
Login

↓

Username

Password

↓

Anyone on the network can intercept the data.
```

With HTTPS

```text
Encrypted Data

↓

Only the server can decrypt it.
```


---
# SSL/TLS Certificate

HTTPS works using an SSL/TLS certificate.

```text
Browser

↓

SSL Handshake

↓

Encrypted Connection

↓

Secure Communication
```

The 🔒 padlock icon in the browser indicates a secure HTTPS connection.


---
# HTTP vs HTTPS

| HTTP               | HTTPS                                 |
| ------------------ | ------------------------------------- |
| Not Secure         | Secure                                |
| Port 80            | Port 443                              |
| No Encryption      | Encrypted                             |
| Slightly Faster    | Slightly Slower (Encryption Overhead) |
| No SSL Certificate | Requires SSL/TLS Certificate          |


---
# Example of HTTP

```text
http://example.com/login
```

Request

```text
username=Rahul

password=1234
```

Anyone monitoring the network could potentially read this information.


---
# Example of HTTPS

```text
https://example.com/login
```

The data is encrypted before being sent, making it unreadable to anyone intercepting the traffic.


